On 12 Sep 2025, at 5:37=E2=80=AFPM, raffaellanz@icloud.com<mailto:raffaella=
nz@icloud.com> wrote:

Kia ora, Grant and Claim Maager/Team,
Thank you for proposing to bring the stakeholders together and provide a co=
nsidered response. While I look forward to receiving written reply to my sp=
ecific questions=E2=80=94could you please confirm when I=E2=80=99ll receive=
 it and suggest a meeting date with an attendee list?  To keep things profe=
ssional and efficient, could we agree on clear deliverables and a test-led =
plan? To promote progress, I=E2=80=99m sharing my initial questions on the =
documents received. I haven=E2=80=99t obtained professional advice yet, so =
I reserve the right to ask further questions, seek clarification, and provi=
de additional feedback.
Fairness & participation
From the ASURNZ report there were two assessment sessions (11 and 21 August=
). I wasn=E2=80=99t invited to the briefings or either site inspection. I a=
ppreciate this may have been an oversight, but it leaves me without visibil=
ity of the brief given to ASURNZ and what they actually saw on the day.
To balance the process, I kindly propose that Tower funds an independent in=
sured-side assessment with me directly engaged; and that I am permitted a o=
ne-on-one session with ASURNZ, as Grant had, so I can brief them directly a=
nd ask questions.
I=E2=80=99d also be grateful for the raw site notes and photo log from thos=
e two attendances, and for inclusion (with reasonable notice) in all future=
 briefings, site visits, and communications.
Fire chemistry & severity
FENZ records show spa-pool chlorine/oxidisers stored in the origin cupboard=
, a HAZMAT requirement at dispatch, and escalation to a second alarm; ASURN=
Z also records cavity smoke migration and roof-edge heat (deformed soffit, =
melted gutter). Smoke odour remains three months later. Taken together, the=
se factors indicate a heightened risk of corrosive/acidic residues and deep=
 smoke penetration into cavities, fixings, the roof assembly, and HVAC, so =
a visual-only approach is not appropriate.
As such, could you please provide a written, insurer-funded plan and schedu=
le setting out methods/standards, pass criteria, dates, and named leads. Th=
e detailed methodology and acceptance thresholds are to be designed and agr=
eed by the appropriate independent experts (hygienist, CPEng structural eng=
ineer, EWRB-licensed electrician/inspector, certifying gasfitter and HVAC t=
echnician, licensed plumber, and a moisture/corrosion specialist) and labor=
atories.  Also it is my understanding that AC2213 (Auckland Council Fire Re=
instatement practice note) expects intrusive investigation and formal sign-=
offs where the primary structure or external moisture/fire systems are affe=
cted, including removal of wet linings/insulation, a CPEng report on the im=
pact to the primary structure, LBP design/supervision where applicable, and=
 s.112 BA04 considerations.
I also believe that at a minimum the plan should address intrusive verifica=
tion of roof/eaves (including underlay, battens, fixings, and truss nail-pl=
ates, with perimeter residue/corrosivity checks where odour is present); ca=
vity assessment on the first-floor south/west elevations and around the fir=
eplace (with removal/cleaning and hygienist clearance before re-lining wher=
e indicated); hygiene and clearance for heat-pump heads and the roof-space =
gas unit/any ducting; whole-installation electrical verification to AS/NZS =
3000 with certification; plumbing system integrity testing and disinfection=
 where indicated; moisture logging and corrosion/pH-chloride screening of r=
epresentative framing/fasteners and masonry; and independent IAQ/surface cl=
earances before re-lining and re-occupation.
Scope adequacy
From the ASURNZ document, there was smoke migration into first-floor caviti=
es with staining on the back of removed plasterboard, and roof-edge heat wi=
th deformed soffit sheeting and a melted gutter. The current scope appears =
focused on apparent damage (clean/smoke-seal, selective electrical checks, =
=E2=80=9Ctest & recommission=E2=80=9D gas) rather than the real damage path=
ways (cavities, roof assembly, services, corrosion).
Respectfully, it is not only the visibly charred beams that can be compromi=
sed. Non-charred structural members, fixings, nail-plates, and brick/mortar=
 exposed to smoke and/or acidic residues can degrade over time if not neutr=
alised or replaced.
Accordingly, could you please explain and evidence:

  *   Why full removal of plasterboard/linings (GIB) in all areas showing c=
avity smoke migration is not proposed, given deep penetration and potential=
 chemical residues.
  *   The evidence-based criteria being used to decide retain vs replace fo=
r framing, fixings, nail-plates and insulation (including any lab threshold=
s, corrosion checks, or moisture limits).
  *   Masonry/brickwork: why cleaning/sealing is proposed instead of replac=
ement of visibly affected brickwork and repointing where residues or acid a=
ttack are indicated; please confirm that any replacement will achieve an id=
entical visual match and quality.
  *   Framing and fixings: how non-charred but smoke-exposed framing and fa=
steners will be assessed (including corrosion and surface pH/chloride check=
s), and the criteria for replacement rather than sealing.
  *   Water/firefighting impacts: what moisture mapping, drying logs, mould=
 assessment/clearance, and wet-insulation replacement are planned for all a=
ffected areas (including ceiling/floor cavities).
  *   Basement storage and wider basement: why there is no building-works s=
cope for the storage area and other basement spaces when contents from thos=
e areas (including items kept in sealed Sistema containers) have been deeme=
d uneconomic to restore; please explain the tests relied upon to consider t=
he building surfaces in those same areas salvageable, and provide the decon=
tamination/repair plan for those spaces.
  *   Deck: current scope limits works to a partial deck replacement when h=
eat/char/smoke exposure is recorded, while Grant has indicated the full dec=
k would be rebuilt; and the tests relied upon (char-depth logs, moisture re=
adings, condition of fixings/hangers/ledger-to-wall, any chloride/pH screen=
ing at the deck-to-wall interface). Please also confirm how the deck and an=
y balustrade/handrail will meet current Code requirements (structure/barrie=
rs) and whether producer statements or LBP supervision are proposed.
  *   Deck: current scope proposes only a partial deck replacement, althoug=
h Grant has recently indicated the full deck would be rebuilt. Could you pl=
ease explain how a patch repair would still achieve a result that is =E2=80=
=9Creasonably equivalent to when new=E2=80=9D in appearance, strength and d=
urability? Could you please also share the results you are relying on for: =
(i) char/heat checks of boards and joists; (ii) moisture readings and decay=
 risk; (iii) removal and inspection of representative hangers, bolts and le=
dger fixings for corrosion/galvanising loss; (iv) ledger-to-wall verificati=
on, including flashing/weep details; (v) chloride/pH screening at the perim=
eter and fixings; and (vi) confirmation that the balustrade/handrail meets =
current requirements. If any results do not meet the engineer=E2=80=99s acc=
eptance criteria, then those components will need to be replaced so the fin=
ished deck is truly as-new.
  *   How each relevant element=E2=80=94whether included in the current sco=
pe or currently omitted (e.g., walls/ceilings, framing, insulation, service=
s, roof-edge components, masonry/brickwork, kitchen, basement storage areas=
, deck, roof-space plant)=E2=80=94will be addressed to achieve the policy s=
tandard of reinstatement =E2=80=9Creasonably equivalent to when new=E2=80=
=9D across appearance, size, functionality, integrity and relative quality;=
 and, for any omitted element, the objective test results and reasoning rel=
ied upon for omission, plus the hold-points/clearances that would trigger i=
ts inclusion in the scope.
  *   Kitchen: why no kitchen works are included despite the earlier heavy =
smoke staining (later cleaned by David, engaged by Tower). Please provide t=
he evidence used to exclude the kitchen (noting that post-clean visuals are=
 not a clearance), the documentation of the cleaning undertaken (before/aft=
er photos, products/methods/SDS), the hygienist=E2=80=99s sampling plan for=
 cabinetry/voids/rangehood/duct, and the electrical/gas/plumbing checks and=
 clearance criteria to confirm the kitchen is safe for normal use.
  *   Roof/eaves and roof space: given the documented melted gutter and def=
ormed soffit=E2=80=94and ongoing smoke odour=E2=80=94why is there no intrus=
ive roof/eaves scope? Please confirm what was actually opened and inspected=
, what (if any) residue or corrosivity testing was done at the eaves/perime=
ter, and whether underlay, battens, fixings and truss nail-plates were asse=
ssed. Please also state whether perimeter wipe sampling is planned, whether=
 any underlay/batten/fixing replacements are allowed for if contamination/h=
eat effects are found, and whether a CPEng will sign off any retained struc=
tural members and roof connections. As a gas heating unit sits in the roof =
space, please confirm how hygiene/clearance of those components and any duc=
ting will be achieved.
Standard of reinstatement
I believe that the policy requires that repairs must reinstate affected par=
ts to a standard reasonably equivalent to when new (appearance, size, funct=
ionality, integrity, relative quality). For visible finishes such as brickw=
ork, replacements should match identically in appearance and quality, so th=
e final result is indistinguishable and durable.
Building consent & AC2213
ASURNZ=E2=80=99s narrative suggests no consent under Schedule 1/s42A. My un=
derstanding is that Auckland Council=E2=80=99s AC2213 indicates consent is =
required for substantial replacement after fire and expects a CPEng report =
addressing the primary structure (including nail-plates/fixings at heat-aff=
ected eaves), HVAC removal/servicing, replacement of wet insulation, and En=
ergy Works certificates for electrical/gas.
Could you please:

  *   Engage a CPEng for the primary-structure report (including the roof/e=
aves zone); and
  *   Obtain Council=E2=80=99s written position for the final scope (consen=
t, or a specific written exemption)? If consent is required, please outline=
 LBPs/Producer Statements and inspections.
Decision-gate and transparency
No repair work or close-ups should occur until all expert reports and clear=
ances above are completed and shared, and we have agreed what needs to be d=
one. Please schedule all inspections and tests with me present, and provide=
 the raw lab reports and photo logs.
Accommodation
Several critical assessments remain outstanding =E2=80=94 chemical penetrat=
ion, roof structure/cavities, and essential services (electrical, gas, wate=
r, HVAC). In light of the FENZ findings and Auckland Council=E2=80=99s AC22=
13 guidance, these should have been anticipated and sequenced from the outs=
et; the resulting delays were preventable and are outside my control. I wil=
l wait for your proposal here. Please let me know how Tower plans to manage=
 accommodation while testing, any consent/design steps, decontamination and=
 reinstatement proceed.
Kindly confirm in writing:

  *   When I will receive your written responses and the meeting date (with=
 agenda).
  *   My inclusion in all future briefings/inspections and provision of pri=
or notes/photos.
  *   The testing plan (roof/eaves, cavities, HVAC/heat pumps & gas heating=
, electrical, gas, water, moisture/corrosion, IAQ) with labs, pass criteria=
, and dates.
  *   A revised scope that is test-led and targets as-new outcomes (not cos=
metic sealing).
  *   The Council/AC2213 path and CPEng engagement (consent or written exem=
ption with reasons).
  *   Temporary accommodation plan for the period until the home is safe an=
d habitable.
Thank you for your cooperation and prompt attention,
Ng=C4=81 mihi,
Raffaella Del Prete


