<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal">&nbsp;<o:p></o:p></p>
</div>
<div>
<div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"font-size:10.0pt">Kia ora, Grant and =
Claim Maager/Team,</span><o:p></o:p></p>
</div>
</div>
<div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"font-size:10.0pt">Thank you for propo=
sing to bring the stakeholders together and provide a considered response. =
While I look forward to receiving written reply to my specific questions=E2=
=80=94could you please confirm when I=E2=80=99ll receive
 it and suggest a meeting date with an attendee list? &nbsp;To keep things =
professional and efficient, could we agree on clear deliverables and a test=
-led plan? To promote progress, I=E2=80=99m sharing my initial questions on=
 the documents received. I haven=E2=80=99t obtained professional
 advice yet, so I reserve the right to ask further questions, seek clarific=
ation, and provide additional feedback.</span><o:p></o:p></p>
</div>
</div>
<div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><u><span style=3D"font-size:10.0pt">Fairness &amp; p=
articipation</span></u><span style=3D"font-size:10.0pt"><br>
From the ASURNZ report there were two assessment sessions (11 and 21 August=
). I wasn=E2=80=99t invited to the briefings or either site inspection. I a=
ppreciate this may have been an oversight, but it leaves me without visibil=
ity of the brief given to ASURNZ and what
 they actually saw on the day.<br>
To balance the process, I kindly propose that Tower funds an independent in=
sured-side assessment with me directly engaged; and that I am permitted a o=
ne-on-one session with ASURNZ, as Grant had, so I can brief them directly a=
nd ask questions.<br>
I=E2=80=99d also be grateful for the raw site notes and photo log from thos=
e two attendances, and for inclusion (with reasonable notice) in all future=
 briefings, site visits, and communications.</span><o:p></o:p></p>
</div>
</div>
<div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><u><span style=3D"font-size:10.0pt">Fire chemistry &=
amp; severity</span></u><span style=3D"font-size:10.0pt"><br>
<span style=3D"color:#212121">FENZ records show spa-pool chlorine/oxidisers=
 stored in the origin cupboard, a HAZMAT requirement at dispatch, and escal=
ation to a second alarm; ASURNZ also records cavity smoke migration and roo=
f-edge heat (deformed soffit, melted
 gutter). Smoke odour remains three months later. Taken together, these fac=
tors indicate a heightened risk of corrosive/acidic residues and deep smoke=
 penetration into cavities, fixings, the roof assembly, and HVAC, so a visu=
al-only approach is not appropriate.</span></span><o:p></o:p></p>
</div>
</div>
<div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"font-size:10.0pt;color:#212121">As su=
ch, could you please provide a written, insurer-funded plan and schedule se=
tting out methods/standards, pass criteria, dates, and named leads. The det=
ailed methodology and acceptance thresholds
 are to be designed and agreed by the appropriate independent experts (hygi=
enist, CPEng structural engineer, EWRB-licensed electrician/inspector, cert=
ifying gasfitter and HVAC technician, licensed plumber, and a moisture/corr=
osion specialist) and laboratories.
 &nbsp;Also it is my understanding that AC2213 (Auckland Council Fire Reins=
tatement practice note) expects intrusive investigation and formal sign-off=
s where the primary structure or external moisture/fire systems are affecte=
d, including removal of wet linings/insulation,
 a CPEng report on the impact to the primary structure, LBP design/supervis=
ion where applicable, and s.112 BA04 considerations.</span><o:p></o:p></p>
</div>
</div>
<div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"font-size:10.0pt;color:#212121">I als=
o believe that at a minimum&nbsp;the plan should address intrusive verifica=
tion of roof/eaves (including underlay, battens, fixings, and truss nail-pl=
ates, with perimeter residue/corrosivity
 checks where odour is present); cavity assessment on the first-floor south=
/west elevations and around the fireplace (with removal/cleaning and hygien=
ist clearance before re-lining where indicated); hygiene and clearance for =
heat-pump heads and the roof-space
 gas unit/any ducting; whole-installation electrical verification to AS/NZS=
 3000 with certification; plumbing system integrity testing and disinfectio=
n where indicated; moisture logging and corrosion/pH-chloride screening of =
representative framing/fasteners
 and masonry; and independent IAQ/surface clearances before re-lining and r=
e-occupation.</span><o:p></o:p></p>
</div>
</div>
<div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><u><span style=3D"font-size:10.0pt">Scope adequacy</=
span></u><span style=3D"font-size:10.0pt"><br>
From the ASURNZ document, there was smoke migration into first-floor caviti=
es with staining on the back of removed plasterboard, and roof-edge heat wi=
th deformed soffit sheeting and a melted gutter. The current scope appears =
focused on apparent damage (clean/smoke-seal,
 selective electrical checks, =E2=80=9Ctest &amp; recommission=E2=80=9D gas=
) rather than the real damage pathways (cavities, roof assembly, services, =
corrosion).<br>
Respectfully, it is not only the visibly charred beams that can be compromi=
sed. Non-charred structural members, fixings, nail-plates, and brick/mortar=
 exposed to smoke and/or acidic residues can degrade over time if not neutr=
alised or replaced.</span><o:p></o:p></p>
</div>
</div>
<div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"font-size:10.0pt">Accordingly, could =
you please explain and evidence:</span><o:p></o:p></p>
</div>
</div>
<ul style=3D"margin-top:0in" type=3D"disc">
<li class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"mso-list:l0 level1 lfo2"><span style=3D"fo=
nt-size:10.0pt">Why full removal of plasterboard/linings (GIB) in all areas=
 showing cavity smoke migration is not proposed, given deep penetration and=
 potential chemical residues.</span><o:p></o:p></li><li class=3D"MsoNormal"=
 style=3D"mso-list:l0 level1 lfo2"><span style=3D"font-size:10.0pt">The evi=
dence-based criteria being used to decide retain vs replace for framing, fi=
xings, nail-plates and insulation (including any lab thresholds, corrosion =
checks,<span class=3D"apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span></span><span styl=
e=3D"font-size:7.5pt">or</span><span class=3D"apple-converted-space"><span =
style=3D"font-size:10.0pt">&nbsp;</span></span><span style=3D"font-size:10.=
0pt">moisture
 limits).</span><o:p></o:p></li><li class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"mso-list:l=
0 level1 lfo2"><span style=3D"font-size:10.0pt">Masonry/brickwork: why clea=
ning/sealing is proposed instead of replacement of visibly affected brickwo=
rk and repointing where residues or acid attack are indicated; please
 confirm that any replacement will achieve an identical visual match and qu=
ality.</span><o:p></o:p></li><li class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"mso-list:l0 l=
evel1 lfo2"><span style=3D"font-size:10.0pt">Framing and fixings: how non-c=
harred but smoke-exposed framing and fasteners will be assessed (including =
corrosion and surface pH/chloride checks), and the criteria for replacement
 rather than sealing.</span><o:p></o:p></li><li class=3D"MsoNormal" style=
=3D"mso-list:l0 level1 lfo2"><span style=3D"font-size:10.0pt">Water/firefig=
hting impacts: what moisture mapping, drying logs, mould assessment/clearan=
ce, and wet-insulation replacement are planned for all affected areas (incl=
uding ceiling/floor
 cavities).</span><o:p></o:p></li><li class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"mso-list=
:l0 level1 lfo2"><span style=3D"font-size:10.0pt">Basement storage and wide=
r basement: why there is no building-works scope for the storage area and o=
ther basement spaces when contents from those areas (including items kept
 in sealed Sistema containers) have been deemed uneconomic to restore; plea=
se explain the tests relied upon to consider the building surfaces in those=
 same areas salvageable, and provide the decontamination/repair plan for th=
ose spaces.</span><o:p></o:p></li><li class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"mso-list=
:l0 level1 lfo2"><span style=3D"font-size:10.0pt">Deck: current scope limit=
s works to a partial deck replacement when heat/char/smoke exposure is reco=
rded, while Grant has indicated the full deck would be rebuilt; and the
 tests relied upon (char-depth logs, moisture readings, condition of fixing=
s/hangers/ledger-to-wall, any chloride/pH screening at the deck-to-wall int=
erface). Please also confirm how the deck and any balustrade/handrail will =
meet current Code requirements (structure/barriers)
 and whether producer statements or LBP supervision are proposed.</span><o:=
p></o:p></li><li class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"mso-list:l0 level1 lfo2"><spa=
n style=3D"font-size:10.0pt">Deck: current scope proposes only a partial de=
ck replacement, although Grant has recently indicated the full deck would b=
e rebuilt. Could you please explain how a patch repair
 would still achieve a result that is =E2=80=9Creasonably equivalent to whe=
n new=E2=80=9D in appearance, strength and durability? Could you please als=
o share the results you are relying on for: (i) char/heat checks of boards =
and joists; (ii) moisture readings and decay risk;
 (iii) removal and inspection of representative hangers, bolts and ledger f=
ixings for corrosion/galvanising loss; (iv) ledger-to-wall verification, in=
cluding flashing/weep details; (v) chloride/pH screening at the perimeter a=
nd fixings; and (vi) confirmation
 that the balustrade/handrail meets current requirements. If any results do=
 not meet the engineer=E2=80=99s acceptance criteria, then those components=
 will need to be replaced so the finished deck is truly as-new.</span><o:p>=
</o:p></li><li class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"mso-list:l0 level1 lfo2"><span =
style=3D"font-size:10.0pt">How each relevant element=E2=80=94whether includ=
ed in the current scope or currently omitted (e.g., walls/ceilings, framing=
, insulation, services, roof-edge components, masonry/brickwork,
 kitchen, basement storage areas, deck, roof-space plant)=E2=80=94will be a=
ddressed to achieve the policy standard of reinstatement =E2=80=9Creasonabl=
y equivalent to when new=E2=80=9D across appearance, size, functionality, i=
ntegrity and relative quality; and, for any omitted element,
 the objective test results and reasoning relied upon for omission, plus th=
e hold-points/clearances that would trigger its inclusion in the scope.</sp=
an><o:p></o:p></li><li class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"mso-list:l0 level1 lfo2=
"><span style=3D"font-size:10.0pt">Kitchen: why no kitchen works are includ=
ed despite the earlier heavy smoke staining (later cleaned by David, engage=
d by Tower). Please provide the evidence used to exclude
 the kitchen (noting that post-clean visuals are not a clearance), the docu=
mentation of the cleaning undertaken (before/after photos, products/methods=
/SDS), the hygienist=E2=80=99s sampling plan for cabinetry/voids/rangehood/=
duct, and the electrical/gas/plumbing checks
 and clearance criteria to confirm the kitchen is safe for normal use.</spa=
n><o:p></o:p></li><li class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"mso-list:l0 level1 lfo2"=
><span style=3D"font-size:10.0pt">Roof/eaves and roof space: given the docu=
mented melted gutter and deformed soffit=E2=80=94and ongoing smoke odour=E2=
=80=94why is there no intrusive roof/eaves scope? Please confirm what was
 actually opened and inspected, what (if any) residue or corrosivity testin=
g was done at the eaves/perimeter, and whether underlay, battens, fixings a=
nd truss nail-plates were assessed. Please also state whether perimeter wip=
e sampling is planned, whether any
 underlay/batten/fixing replacements are allowed for if contamination/heat =
effects are found, and whether a CPEng will sign off any retained structura=
l members and roof connections. As a gas heating unit sits in the roof spac=
e, please confirm how hygiene/clearance
 of those components and any ducting will be achieved.</span><o:p></o:p></l=
i></ul>
<div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><u><span style=3D"font-size:10.0pt">Standard of rein=
statement</span></u><span style=3D"font-size:10.0pt"><br>
<span style=3D"color:#212121">I believe that the policy requires that&nbsp;=
repairs must reinstate affected parts to a standard reasonably equivalent t=
o when new (appearance, size, functionality, integrity, relative quality). =
For visible finishes such as brickwork,
 replacements should match identically in appearance and quality, so the fi=
nal result is indistinguishable and durable.</span></span><o:p></o:p></p>
</div>
</div>
<div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><u><span style=3D"font-size:10.0pt">Building consent=
 &amp; AC2213</span></u><span style=3D"font-size:10.0pt"><br>
ASURNZ=E2=80=99s narrative suggests no consent under Schedule 1/s42A. My un=
derstanding is that Auckland Council=E2=80=99s AC2213 indicates consent is =
required for substantial replacement after fire and expects a CPEng report =
addressing the primary structure (including nail-plates/fixings
 at heat-affected eaves), HVAC removal/servicing, replacement of wet insula=
tion, and Energy Works certificates for electrical/gas.<br>
Could you please:</span><o:p></o:p></p>
</div>
</div>
<ul style=3D"margin-top:0in" type=3D"disc">
<li class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"mso-list:l11 level1 lfo3"><span style=3D"f=
ont-size:10.0pt">Engage a CPEng for the primary-structure report (including=
 the roof/eaves zone); and</span><o:p></o:p></li><li class=3D"MsoNormal" st=
yle=3D"mso-list:l11 level1 lfo3"><span style=3D"font-size:10.0pt">Obtain Co=
uncil=E2=80=99s written position for the final scope (consent, or a specifi=
c written exemption)? If consent is required, please outline LBPs/Producer =
Statements and inspections.</span><o:p></o:p></li></ul>
<div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><u><span style=3D"font-size:10.0pt">Decision-gate an=
d transparency</span></u><span style=3D"font-size:10.0pt"><br>
No repair work or close-ups should occur until all expert reports and clear=
ances above are completed and shared, and we have agreed what needs to be d=
one. Please schedule all inspections and tests with me present, and provide=
 the raw lab reports and photo logs.</span><o:p></o:p></p>
</div>
</div>
<div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><u><span style=3D"font-size:10.0pt">Accommodation</s=
pan></u><span style=3D"font-size:10.0pt"><br>
Several critical assessments remain outstanding =E2=80=94 chemical penetrat=
ion, roof structure/cavities, and essential services (electrical, gas, wate=
r, HVAC). In light of the FENZ findings and Auckland Council=E2=80=99s AC22=
13 guidance, these should have been anticipated
 and sequenced from the outset; the resulting delays were preventable and a=
re outside my control. I will wait for your proposal here. Please let me kn=
ow how Tower plans to manage accommodation while testing, any consent/desig=
n steps, decontamination and reinstatement
 proceed.</span><o:p></o:p></p>
</div>
</div>
<div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"font-size:10.0pt">Kindly confirm in w=
riting:</span><o:p></o:p></p>
</div>
</div>
<ul style=3D"margin-top:0in" type=3D"disc">
<li class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"mso-list:l13 level1 lfo4"><span style=3D"f=
ont-size:10.0pt">When I will receive your written responses and the meeting=
 date (with agenda).</span><o:p></o:p></li><li class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D=
"mso-list:l13 level1 lfo4"><span style=3D"font-size:10.0pt">My inclusion in=
 all future briefings/inspections and provision of prior notes/photos.</spa=
n><o:p></o:p></li><li class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"mso-list:l13 level1 lfo4=
"><span style=3D"font-size:10.0pt">The testing plan (roof/eaves, cavities, =
HVAC/heat pumps &amp; gas heating, electrical, gas, water, moisture/corrosi=
on, IAQ) with labs, pass criteria, and dates.</span><o:p></o:p></li><li cla=
ss=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"mso-list:l13 level1 lfo4"><span style=3D"font-siz=
e:10.0pt">A revised scope that is test-led and targets as-new outcomes (not=
 cosmetic sealing).</span><o:p></o:p></li><li class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"=
mso-list:l13 level1 lfo4"><span style=3D"font-size:10.0pt">The Council/AC22=
13 path and CPEng engagement (consent or written exemption with reasons).</=
span><o:p></o:p></li><li class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"mso-list:l13 level1 l=
fo4"><span style=3D"font-size:10.0pt">Temporary accommodation plan for the =
period until the home is safe and habitable.</span><o:p></o:p></li></ul>
<div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"font-size:10.0pt">Thank you for your =
cooperation and prompt attention,</span><o:p></o:p></p>
</div>
</div>
<div>
<div>
